{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Csx3DxDKQ6HoMay4bpCUx5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see the issues clearly:\n\n1. **`elasticsearch` cluster (8.11.1)**: \n   - `elasticsearch-0` log shows it received plaintext HTTP traffic on an HTTPS channel - this explains the exit code 52 from curl without SSL. The cluster uses TLS but the es-http service doesn't use TLS.\n   - The cluster was recently restarted (at 19:53:27, master changed to elasticsearch-2 and then elasticsearch-1 joined)\n   - It's the cluster `es-cluster` (name) with nodes `elasticsearch-0`, `elasticsearch-1`, `elasticsearch-2`\n   - This is version 8.11.1 with xpack security enabled\n\n2. **`es-cluster` cluster (7.17.9)**:\n   - `es-cluster-0` is failing to resolve the DNS names for the other cluster nodes, which is preventing it from discovering and joining the cluster\n   - This is version 7.17.9 and uses the `es-config` ConfigMap\n   - The headless service isn't properly resolving for the nodes\n\nI'm realizing the actual issue: the `es-cluster` StatefulSet references a headless service named `es-cluster`, but looking at the available services, there's no headless service with that name—only `es-headless`, `es-http`, and `minio`. Without the matching headless service, the DNS names the pods are trying to reach simply don't exist, which is why the resolution is failing and the cluster can't form. The issue is that the StatefulSet specifies `serviceName: es-cluster`, which requires a headless service with that exact name to exist in the elasticsearch namespace. Looking at the available services—`es-headless`, `es-http`, and `minio`—there's no `es-cluster` service, so the DNS names in the discovery configuration can't resolve properly. there's no `es-cluster` service to match the StatefulSet's `serviceName: es-cluster`, so the seed hosts in the ConfigMap can't resolve `es-cluster-0.es-cluster.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`. The `elasticsearch` StatefulSet works fine because it references the existing `es-headless` service with the right selector, but the `es-cluster` pods keep restarting because they can't discover each other without their headless service. to connect to `es-cluster-0/1/2` pods that don't exist. Yet the `elasticsearch` pods are actually running and joined the cluster successfully, which means either the config isn't being used as expected or there's something else overriding it. hosts: `es-cluster-0.es-cluster.elasticsearch...`. But the elasticsearch pods are actually named `elasticsearch-0`, `elasticsearch-1`, `elasticsearch-2`, and with `node.name` set to the pod name, there's a mismatch between what the config specifies in `cluster.initial_master_nodes` (`es-cluster-0`, `es-cluster-1`, `es-cluster-2`) and the actual node names. This should have prevented the cluster from forming, yet it did successfully join.\n\nLooking at the StatefulSet spec, it's definitely mounting the `es-config` ConfigMap as its config volume. The timing is odd though—the pods started between 19:25-19:30, but the ConfigMap was created at 19:26:49, suggesting either the pods used an earlier version of the config or the ConfigMap was updated after the fact.\n\nThe `restartedAt` annotation shows 19:46:59 UTC, which is after the ConfigMap was created, and the elasticsearch-0 pod logs show it started at 19:53:27 UTC and successfully joined the cluster with the other nodes. So somehow the cluster is functioning despite what should be a config mismatch.\n\nLooking at the elasticsearch StatefulSet environment variables, I see `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` and `ES_JAVA_OPTS` are set, but there's no `POD_NAME` env var defined. Yet the `es-config` ConfigMap references `${POD_NAME}` for the `node.name` setting, which means that variable wouldn't actually be substituted in the elasticsearch StatefulSet's configuration.\n\nI'm realizing the elasticsearch StatefulSet might not be using the `es-config` ConfigMap the way I initially thought. The volume mount points directly to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/elasticsearch.yml` as a single file mount, not a full directory mount with subPath, so the configuration setup is different than what I was assuming. The `es-cluster` StatefulSet explicitly filters the ConfigMap to only include the `elasticsearch.yml` key, while the `elasticsearch` StatefulSet mounts the entire ConfigMap without that filter. Even though both reference the same ConfigMap with potentially incorrect seed_hosts configuration, the `elasticsearch` cluster is running without restarts, which suggests the seed_hosts setting might not be critical for its operation or there's something else allowing it to function despite the misconfiguration. The `es-cluster` pods can't form a persistent cluster because the headless service they're trying to discover each other through doesn't exist, causing DNS resolution to fail on restart. But wait—if the pods are currently Running despite 7 restarts, maybe some have managed to form a cluster anyway. Let me think about what's actually happening here. The verification checks the `elasticsearch` cluster (8.11.1) through the `es-http` service, which selects the right pods, and the logs show that cluster has a master node. If the `cluster.initial_master_nodes` config lists `es-cluster-0/1/2` but the actual node names are `elasticsearch-0/1/2`, the initial master election should fail since nothing matches. But the cluster clearly formed, which suggests persisted cluster state from disk—the PVCs retained data from a previous formation even after the pod restart, allowing the cluster to recover without needing the initial_master_nodes bootstrap.\n\nThe real problem is simpler: the `es-http` service tries to connect to the Elasticsearch cluster without TLS, but the cluster requires HTTPS, and the logs show it's rejecting plaintext HTTP connections.\n\nThere's a contradiction here though—the `es-config` ConfigMap explicitly disables security and HTTPS, yet the `elasticsearch` cluster is still enforcing it. This suggests the pods are running with security configuration from disk (the original setup) rather than the current ConfigMap content, even though the ConfigMap was updated during the stage_10 setup.\n\nLet me verify the actual state by checking what the Elasticsearch cluster exposes via HTTPS, and I should also look into what the `elastic-password` secret contains.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9482,"cache_read_input_tokens":39316,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9482},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2641e37e-6abc-4f39-a7ba-981ed9487784","uuid":"e0c04d4b-30ee-49ed-aa96-0875ce993203","request_id":"req_011CcfkTFZw9uNPumZUM21QV"}
