{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PCskqGWCm6hqQMaFXPUNT9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I fully understand the setup. Let me trace through what happened:\n\n**Stage 10 setup (precondition apply path since probe passed - it found `es-cluster` sts and `es-http` svc and at least 1 running pod):**\n\nThe `es_env_ready` probe was:\n```\nkubectl -n elasticsearch get sts es-cluster >/dev/null 2>&1 && kubectl -n elasticsearch get svc es-http >/dev/null 2>&1 && [ \"$(kubectl -n elasticsearch get pods -l app=es-cluster --field-selector=status.phase=Running 2>/dev/null | grep -c Running)\" -ge 1 ]\n```\n\nThe probe passed because the StatefulSet, service, and running pod all existed, so the apply step was skipped and it went straight to verify. But I need to reconsider KARMA's precondition logic here—if the probe passes, it means the desired state is already met, so `on_probe_fail: skip` would only skip the apply when the probe fails, not when it succeeds.\n```\n` → skip apply. Let me look at the actual KARMA code to clarify this. Looking at the probe command in the logs, it's checking if the StatefulSet, Service, and at least one Running pod exist. The fact that we're progressing to stage_10 suggests the probe either passed or failed in a way that allowed execution to continue.\n```\n\nActually, I think I see the issue now. The `es_env_ready` precondition has `on_probe_fail: skip`, which means if the probe fails, it skips that precondition unit entirely. But if the probe passes, it skips the apply step. So either way, the apply doesn't run—the only way apply would execute is if the probe failed AND there was no `on_probe_fail: skip` directive. Since the cluster is running with existing resources from previous stages, the probe must have passed, confirming that the Elasticsearch environment was already set up.\n\nThe stage 10 fault was actually injected during a precondition apply step that ran earlier. That apply step modifies the Elasticsearch config to use incorrect seed hosts (pointing to `.default.svc.cluster.local` instead of `.elasticsearch.svc.cluster.local`), then orchestrates a rolling restart by scaling the StatefulSet down to 2 replicas, deleting the persistent volume for the third node, and scaling back up to 3 replicas. The probe passed so the fault setup wasn't applied, meaning the ConfigMap still has the correct namespace. The real issue is that the StatefulSet references a headless service named `es-cluster` that doesn't actually exist in the cluster—only `es-headless`, `es-http`, and `minio` services are present, which is why the pods can't resolve their DNS names and keep restarting.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3106,"cache_read_input_tokens":59399,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3106},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2641e37e-6abc-4f39-a7ba-981ed9487784","uuid":"cc1c3092-4a40-441d-b69a-10570ecab878","request_id":"req_011Ccfke9dJwJXzreV9ELQ3p"}
