{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0134c5vZYnxKuaG5p3bYYWSZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the oracle completely. It:\n1. Detects the scheme (HTTP first, then HTTPS fallback) via `curl -o /dev/null -w '%{http_code}'`\n2. Gets nodes via `/_cat/nodes?format=json`\n3. Checks cluster health via `/_cluster/health?wait_for_status=yellow&wait_for_nodes=<expected>&timeout=10s`\n4. Checks app-data via `/<INDEX>/_count`\n\nThe oracle uses `SERVICE = \"es-http\"` to make these calls.\n\nThe current `es-http` service points to `app=elasticsearch` (the 8.11.1 cluster with TLS). \n\nWhen the oracle probes the scheme, it tries HTTP first against the TLS-enabled cluster, which closes the connection immediately with a plaintext rejection rather than returning an HTTP status code. This means curl would fail on the initial HTTP attempt.\n\nThe oracle then switches to HTTPS, which succeeds and returns 200 OK. From there it can authenticate with the credentials and verify the cluster has 3 nodes with green health status. However, the critical issue is that the `app-data` index doesn't actually exist in the elasticsearch cluster that `es-http` points to, so the oracle's index count check would fail.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6506,"cache_read_input_tokens":64852,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6506},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"2641e37e-6abc-4f39-a7ba-981ed9487784","uuid":"d0112cac-f978-4d9a-8bd8-b2675b830e69","request_id":"req_011Ccfkj9L5pfTNA962tuhE4"}
